<title>Finding Probability of Events</title>

</head>
<body>
   <!--   <objref idref="determine_sample_space"/>-->
    <p><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T105510-0400" comment="I modified this to use the language that was used up to this point -- the term &quot;random experiment&quot; is not introduced and defined until the next page, so I think it&apos;s best to avoid using it on this page."?>In
            the previous module, we introduced probability as a way to quantify the uncertainty that
            arises from
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104355-0400"?>conducting<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104352-0400" content="repeating random"?>
            experiments <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104442-0400"?>using a
            random sample of the population of
            interest<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104504-0400" content="such as selecting an individual and recording his/her blood type"?>.
            <?oxy_comment_end?>We saw that the probability of an event (for example, the event that
            a randomly chosen person
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104043-0400"?>has
            <?oxy_insert_end?>blood type O) can be estimated by the relative frequency with which
            the event occurs in a long series of trials. So we
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104316-0400"?>would
            <?oxy_insert_end?>collect data from lots of individuals to estimate the probability of
            someone having blood type O. </p>
    
    
    <p>In this
            module<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101106T104545-0400"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
